reviews.text:
I first visited this dentist for a check-up and to inquire about getting braces because my mom made an appointment for me on 28/8/2024. During that visit, I asked the dentist if I needed any fillings. The dentist assured me that everything looked fine according to the scan, and there were no fillings required.

However, on the following day, 29/8/2024, I received a message stating that I did, in fact, need fillings. I was confused because before leaving the clinic, I specifically asked if I needed any, and the dentist had confidently said no (this was the first instance of unprofessionalism).

I returned to the dentist on 2/9/2024 to get the fillings done and to proceed with braces. After my first appointment, I was given the option of either Invisalign or metal braces. I chose metal braces. After completing the fillings, the dentist placed 8 rubber bands between my teeth, explaining that this was to create gaps. I was told the bands needed to stay for at least a week. Unfortunately, I experienced significant discomfort throughout that week, as my teeth became weak and chewing was painful.

On 5/9/2024, I texted the clinic to ask if I could come in earlier because the pain was getting worse. I was then told (the second instance of unprofessional treatment) that braces were no longer recommended at this time because I needed a root canal first. I was also informed that it typically takes 3-6 months after a root canal before braces can be done. This meant that during my previous visit, the dentist had placed the rubber bands in my mouth for no valid reason, causing me unnecessary pain.

I was advised to return to the clinic for a root canal treatment on 7/9/2024, after nearly a week of avoidable discomfort. During this visit, the dentist said anesthetic wasn‚Äôt necessary because the tooth was dead, so there wouldn‚Äôt be any pain. However, during my follow-up visit on 13/9/2024, the dentist planned to place a rubber dam before starting the root canal. She explained that anesthetic was necessary because the process might cause pain. However, after administering the anesthetic, the dentist made two unsuccessful attempts to attach the rubber dam and then decided to proceed with the root canal without it.

This left me questioning why the anesthetic was administered if the procedure could be done without the rubber dam. This was the third instance of unprofessional treatment.

Despite the unprofessional treatment from the dentist, I would like to acknowledge that the front desk staff has been very helpful and friendly throughout my visits. Their assistance made the scheduling and follow-ups smoother and more pleasant, which I truly appreciated.

Overall, though, I am deeply dissatisfied with the dental service, as it caused me unnecessary discomfort and confusion. I feel that the treatment provided was unprofessional at multiple stages.

reviews.text:
I have visited this clinic thrice for two different treatments and have had extremely poor experiences with two different doctors. I strongly advise caution to anyone considering this clinic.

1. First Treatment: Whitening (with Chinese Doctor)
My first appointment was for a whitening treatment. While I was generally accepting, the procedure was done so aggressively that my gums developed a wound and felt extreme stinging. A professional should be able to perform this common procedure without causing injury (did my whitening treatment at other clinic before - not first timer)

2. Second Treatment: Scaling and Black Metal Filling Change (with Indian Doctor)
I returned for a scaling treatment, but also asked if my old black metal filling could be changed to a new white composite filling. The Indian doctor immediately said "can" without any consultation about potential risks, consequences, or the suitability of the tooth for the change. During the filling procedure, the doctor was extremely hesitant and unprofessional. She asked me more than 10 times if the filling was "okay" and in same flat with the other teeth. As a doctor, I expect them to use their own professional judgment and instruments to determine the correct bite and contour, not rely repeatedly on the patient. This made me feel she was unexperienced and unsure of how to properly trim and contour the filing.

3. The Consequences and Third Visit (with Chinese Doctor)
A few days after the filling change, I could not eat or chew using that tooth due to pain and discomfort, indicating the filling was not done correctly. I went back for a check-up. The Chinese doctor examined the tooth and said that the tooth "might be cracked" because of the changing from metal to the white filing. The permanent solution is by doing a crown. Haha went there with a NO PROBLEM tooth condition and the result that I received? MAJOR PROBLEM !!!

This clinic seems to have unexperienced doctors who perform rushed, inadequate work that ultimately creates more problems, leading to further, more costly treatments and wasting my time

reviews.name: Jac T
reviews.text:
This review comes very late but it‚Äôs something that parents should be aware of, on the importance of choosing and communicating with the right dentist for your kids.
Growing up, I visited Dr Ho as a child to have dental routine check ups, scaling and filling as treatments. As one of the more popular private practices in the town in the late 90s and early 2000, it‚Äôs considered a luxury to visit as parents want our teeth to be better taken care of, rather than relying on government funded practice as more time can be spent to attend to the patient in the private.

Yet, Dr Ho failed to identify the possibility of ankylosed tooth at the age of 6-9 years old and underbite issue that both warrant a referral to seek early treatment. None of this was communicated to parents back then and i see such as a huge failure as a primary dentist and wondered on her capability as a dentist. As such, this impacted the life of the patient with misaligned bite that had been left too late to be corrected but left with full orthognathic surgery option, implant, and orthodonticx  It‚Äôs not just aesthetic issue alone, but also this was also causing other health issues for eg airway and sinus and TMJ being the essentials, and list goes on.

I have not visited this practice since I understood the context as a young adult, thus my personal record will not be recent enough to reflect on their patient record, and given that  I have a different name on the register. Although it‚Äôs unfair to review this clinic as a zero star (if I could give a zero) for other good dentists that might be out here, I want to bring it to her attention of her failure in her dentist career since I noticed she also had a cert in implantology. Wonder how the expansion of the clinic happens with her being the founder/cofounder and being this unknowledgeable. I am not the only patient who suffered from this negligence of hers, two more people I personally know had issues not referred as a kid for treatment but not to the bad extent of mine.

So choose your treating dentist appropriately, as early intervention in kids that require referral and treatment is crucial! All the golden time for intervention and treatment should not be missed as the gums also recess as you age.
